## 🟢 FIRST TIME ONLY (on your local project)

### ✅ 1) Go to your project folder

Open a terminal (Command Prompt, PowerShell, macOS/Linux Terminal), then:

```bash
cd path/to/your/project
```

🔹 **What this does:** Makes sure you’re *inside* the folder where your project files live.

---

### ✅ 2) Initialize Git

```bash
git init
```

🔹 **What this does:** Creates a hidden `.git/` folder in your project. This marks your folder as a Git repository and starts tracking changes.

---

### ✅ 3) Add your remote repository

First, go to GitHub.com, log into your account, click **New Repository**, create an empty repo (no README), and copy the URL it gives you—e.g.:

```
https://github.com/your-username/your-repo.git
```

Then in your terminal:

```bash
git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/your-repo.git
```

🔹 **What this does:** Links your local Git repo with your repo on GitHub—so you can push/pull changes.

---

### ✅ 4) Add all project files to Git

```bash
git add .
```

🔹 **What this does:** Stages *all* files in the project so Git knows you want to include them in the next snapshot/commit.

---

### ✅ 5) Make your first commit

```bash
git commit -m "Initial commit with all project files"
```

🔹 **What this does:** Creates a permanent snapshot of your staged files with a message describing what’s in it.

---

### ✅ 6) Push to GitHub

```bash
git branch -M main        # (Optional) Renames your branch to 'main' if needed
git push -u origin main
```

🔹 **What this does:** Uploads your commits to GitHub.
🔹 `-u` sets `origin/main` as the default upstream branch so you can just run `git push` later.

🎉 **Your project is now on GitHub!**

---

## 🟡 DAILY WORKFLOW (every day you work on your code)

Here’s what you’ll do every time you want to upload your day’s work:

---

### ✅ 1) See what changed

```bash
git status
```

🔹 **What this does:** Shows what files you modified since your last commit. Very useful to avoid accidentally missing anything.

---

### ✅ 2) Add the changed files

```bash
git add .
```

🔹 **What this does:** Stages your changed files so they’ll be included in your next commit.

---

### ✅ 3) Commit your changes

```bash
git commit -m "Describe today's changes here"
```

🔹 **What this does:** Records a new snapshot of the changes you staged, with a message to help you remember what you did.

---

### ✅ 4) Push your changes to GitHub

```bash
git push
```

🔹 **What this does:** Uploads your new commits to your GitHub repo.

---

## 🔵 OPTIONAL: Checking history

See your full commit history with:

```bash
git log
```

This shows who made what changes and when.
🔹 Use it to track your progress or go back to older versions.

---

## 🔴 OPTIONAL: Reverting to an old version

If you need to discard your current work and go back to a previous commit:

1️⃣ Run:

```bash
git log
```

Copy the hash of the commit you want.

2️⃣ Then reset:

```bash
git reset --hard <commit-hash>
```

3️⃣ Finally, if you want GitHub to match your local reset:

```bash
git push -f
```

🔹 **What this does:** Overwrites your remote repo with your local repo’s state.
🚨 **Caution:** this will discard newer commits on GitHub—use only if you’re sure!

---

## 🚨 TIPS

✅ **Write clear commit messages** like:

* `"Fix bug in resume parsing"`
* `"Add candidate skills extraction logic"`
* `"Refactor location extraction"`

✅ **.gitignore**: If you ever need to exclude files/folders (like logs or secrets), add a file called `.gitignore` with patterns of what you want Git to ignore.

---

## 🔵 TL;DR DAILY CHECKLIST

* `git status` → What changed?
* `git add .` → Stage changes
* `git commit -m "Your message"` → Save snapshot
* `git push` → Upload to GitHub

